					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Dat=
a visualization</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Michelsonmorley-boxplot.svg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/f/fa/Michelsonmorley-boxplot.svg/500px-Michelsonmorley-boxplot.svg.png"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"340" height=3D"340" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"432" data-file-height=3D"432"></a><figcaption>Box plot o=
f data from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelson%E2%80%93=
Morley_experiment#Michelson_experiment_(1881)" title=3D"Michelson=E2=80=93M=
orley experiment">Michelson experiment</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statistics" titl=
e=3D"Descriptive statistics">descriptive statistics</a>, a <b>box plot</b> =
or <b>boxplot</b> is a method for demonstrating graphically the locality, s=
pread and skewness groups of numerical data through their <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartile" title=3D"Quartile">quartiles</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Box_plot#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In addition to the box on a box plot, there can be lines (which are =
called <i>whiskers</i>) extending from the box indicating variability outsi=
de the upper and lower quartiles, thus, the plot is also called the <b>box-=
and-whisker plot</b> and the <b>box-and-whisker diagram</b>. <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">Outliers</a> that dif=
fer significantly from the rest of the dataset<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> may be plotted as individual points beyond the whiskers on th=
e box-plot. Box plots are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-para=
metric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-parametric">non-parametric</a>: =
they display variation in samples of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical population">statistical p=
opulation</a> without making any assumptions of the underlying <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability=
 distribution">statistical distribution</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-3"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> (though Tukey's boxplot assumes symmetry for the whiskers and nor=
mality for their length).
</p><p>The spacings in each subsection of the box-plot indicate the degree =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_dispersion" title=
=3D"Statistical dispersion">dispersion</a> (spread) and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness" title=3D"Skewness">skewness</a> of the data=
, which are usually described using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Five-number_summary" title=3D"Five-number summary">five-number summar=
y</a>. In addition, the box-plot allows one to visually estimate various <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-estimator" title=3D"L-estimator">L=
-estimators</a>, notably the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter=
quartile_range" title=3D"Interquartile range">interquartile range</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midhinge" title=3D"Midhinge">midhinge<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Range_(statistics)" title=3D"=
Range (statistics)">range</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mid=
-range" title=3D"Mid-range">mid-range</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Trimean" title=3D"Trimean">trimean</a>. Box plots can be drawn=
 either horizontally or vertically.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The range-bar method was first introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mary_Eleanor_Spear" title=3D"Mary Eleanor Spear">Mary Eleanor=
 Spear</a> in her book "Charting Statistics" in 1952<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_=
note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> and again in her book "Practical Charting Techniques" in=
 1969.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The box-and-whisker plot wa=
s first introduced in 1970 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John=
_Tukey" title=3D"John Tukey">John Tukey</a>, who later published on the sub=
ject in his book "Exploratory Data Analysis" in 1977.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0=
_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot=
#cite_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Elements">Elements</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Elements"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Box-Plot_mit_Min-Max_Abstand.png" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/5/55/Box-Plot_mit_Min-Max_Abstand.png/250px-Box-Plot_mit_Min-Max_A=
bstand.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"187" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"715" data-file-height=3D"536"></a><figcaption=
>Box-plot with whiskers from minimum to maximum</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Box-Plot_mit_Interquartilsabstand.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/2/2b/Box-Plot_mit_Interquartilsabstand.png/250px-Box-Plot_mi=
t_Interquartilsabstand.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"187"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"715" data-file-height=3D"536"=
></a><figcaption>The same box-plot with whiskers drawn within the 1.5 IQR v=
alue</figcaption></figure>
<p>A boxplot is a standardized way of displaying the dataset based on the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five-number_summary" title=3D"Five-=
number summary">five-number summary</a>: the minimum, the maximum, the samp=
le median, and the first and third quartiles.
</p>
<ul><li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_minimum" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample minimum">Minimum</a> (<i>Q</i><sub>0</sub>=
 or 0th <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentile" title=3D"Perce=
ntile">percentile</a>)</b>: the lowest data point in the data set excluding=
 any outliers</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_maximum" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Sample maximum">Maximum</a> (<i>Q</i><sub>4</sub> or 10=
0th percentile)</b>: the highest data point in the data set excluding any o=
utliers</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=3D"Median">Me=
dian</a> (<i>Q</i><sub>2</sub> or 50th percentile)</b>: the middle value in=
 the data set</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_quartile" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"First quartile">First quartile</a> (<i>Q</i><sub>1</sub=
> or 25th percentile)</b>: also known as the <i>lower quartile</i> <i>q</i>=
<sub><i>n</i></sub>(0.25), it is the median of the lower half of the datase=
t.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Third_quartile" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Third quartile">Third quartile</a> (<i>Q</i><sub>3</sub=
> or 75th percentile)</b>: also known as the <i>upper quartile</i> <i>q</i>=
<sub><i>n</i></sub>(0.75), it is the median of the upper half of the datase=
t.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>In addition to the minimum and maximum values used to construct a box-pl=
ot, another important element that can also be employed to obtain a box-plo=
t is the interquartile range (IQR), as denoted below:
</p>
<ul><li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interquartile_range" ti=
tle=3D"Interquartile range">Interquartile range</a> (IQR)</b>: the distance=
 between the upper and lower quartiles</li></ul>
