</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/55207ed597c8171bd024775fabf80dc36b1be30e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:38.419ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
text{IQR}}=3DQ_{3}-Q_{1}=3Dq_{n}(0.75)-q_{n}(0.25)}"></span></dd></dl></dd>=
</dl>
<p>A box-plot usually includes two parts, a box and a set of whiskers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Box">Box</h3><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Box"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The box is drawn from <i>Q</i><sub>1</sub> to <i>Q</i><sub>3</sub> with =
a horizontal line drawn inside it to denote the median. Some box plots incl=
ude an additional character to represent the mean of the data.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-frigge_hoaglin_iglewicz2_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-frigge_hoaglin_iglewicz2-8"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Whiskers">Whiskers</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Whiskers"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The whiskers must end at an observed data point, but can be defined in v=
arious ways. In the most straightforward method, the boundary of the lower =
whisker is the minimum value of the data set, and the boundary of the upper=
 whisker is the maximum value of the data set. Because of this variability,=
 it is appropriate to describe the convention that is being used for the wh=
iskers and outliers in the caption of the box-plot.
</p><p>Another popular choice for the boundaries of the whiskers is based o=
n the 1.5 IQR value. From above the upper quartile (<b><i>Q</i><sub>3</sub>=
</b>), a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out and a whisker is dra=
wn <i>up to</i> the largest observed data point from the dataset that falls=
 within this distance. Similarly, a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measur=
ed out below the lower quartile (<b><i>Q</i><sub>1</sub></b>) and a whisker=
 is drawn <i>down to</i> the lowest observed data point from the dataset th=
at falls within this distance. Because the whiskers must end at an observed=
 data point, the whisker lengths can look unequal, even though 1.5 IQR is t=
he same for both sides. All other observed data points outside the boundary=
 of the whiskers are plotted as <b>outliers</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_not=
e-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The outliers can be plotted on the box-plot as a dot, a s=
mall circle, a star, <i>etc.</i> (see example below).
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Box_Plot_Picture.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:/=
/upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Box_Plot_Picture.png/330=
px-Box_Plot_Picture.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"279" height=3D"92" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4407" data-file-height=3D"1455"><=
/a><figcaption>A box plot representing data</figcaption></figure>
<p>There are other representations in which the whiskers can stand for seve=
ral other things, such as:
</p>
<ul><li>One <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" ti=
tle=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a> above and below the mean =
of the data set</li>
<li>The 9th percentile and the 91st percentile of the data set</li>
<li>The 2nd percentile and the 98th percentile of the data set</li></ul>
<p>Rarely, box-plot can be plotted without the whiskers. This can be approp=
riate for sensitive information to avoid whiskers (and outliers) disclosing=
 actual values observed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DGRW_11-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-DGRW-11"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The unusual percentiles 2%, 9%, 91%, 98% are sometimes used for whis=
ker cross-hatches and whisker ends to depict the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Seven-number_summary" title=3D"Seven-number summary">seven-n=
umber summary</a>. If the data are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normally distributed</a=
>, the locations of the seven marks on the box plot will be equally spaced.=
 On some box plots, a cross-hatch is placed before the end of each whisker.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Variations">Variations</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Variations"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fourboxplots.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Fo=
urboxplots.svg/330px-Fourboxplots.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"330"=
 height=3D"330" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"630" data-file=
-height=3D"630"></a><figcaption>Four box plots, with and without notches an=
d variable width</figcaption></figure>
<p>Since the mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_W.=
_Tukey" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"John W. Tukey">John W. Tukey</a> fir=
st popularized this type of visual data display in 1969, several variations=
 on the classical box plot have been developed, and the two most commonly f=
ound variations are the variable-width box plots and the notched box plots.
</p><p><b>Variable-width box</b> plots illustrate the size of each group wh=
ose data is being plotted by making the width of the box proportional to th=
e size of the group. A popular convention is to make the box width proporti=
onal to the square root of the size of the group.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mcgill=
_tukey_larsen_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-mcgill_tukey_larsen-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Notched box</b> plots apply a "notch" or narrowing of the box aro=
und the median. Notches are useful in offering a rough guide of the signifi=
cance of the difference of medians; if the notches of two boxes do not over=
lap, this will provide evidence of a statistically significant difference b=
etween the medians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mcgill_tukey_larsen_12-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-mcgil=
l_tukey_larsen-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The height of the notches is proportional to=
 the interquartile range (IQR) of the sample and is inversely proportional =
to the square root of the size of the sample. However, there is an uncertai=
nty about the most appropriate multiplier (as this may vary depending on th=
e similarity of the variances of the samples).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mcgill_tu=
key_larsen_12-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Box_plot#cite_note-mcgill_tukey_larsen-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The width of the =
notch is arbitrarily chosen to be visually pleasing, and should be consiste=
nt amongst all box plots being displayed on the same page.
</p><p>One convention for obtaining the boundaries of these notches is to u=
se a distance of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><=
span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display=
: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\di=
splaystyle \pm {\frac {1.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=C2=B1<!-- =C2=B1 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mn>1.58</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mtext>&nbsp;IQR</mtext>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <msqrt>
              <mi>n</mi>
            </msqrt>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \pm {\frac {1=
.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/66009e21ab041d7e64df5ec105039738573634fd" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.838ex; width:11.717ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \p=
m {\frac {1.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}}"></span> around the median.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Rboxplotstats_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-Rboxplotstats-13"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><b>Adjusted box</b> plots are intended to describe <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness" title=3D"Skewness">skew distributions</a>=
, and they rely on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medcouple" =
title=3D"Medcouple">medcouple</a> statistic of skewness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Hubert2008_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Box_plot#cite_note-Hubert2008-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For a medcouple value of =
MC, the lengths of the upper and lower whiskers on the box-plot are respect=
ively defined to be:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{matrix}1.5{\text{IQR}}\cdot e^{3{\text{MC}}},&amp;1.5{\text{ IQR}=
}\cdot e^{-4{\text{MC}}}{\text{ if }}{\text{MC}}\geq 0,\\1.5{\text{IQR}}\cd=
ot e^{4{\text{MC}}},&amp;1.5{\text{ IQR}}\cdot e^{-3{\text{MC}}}{\text{ if =
}}{\text{MC}}\leq 0.\end{matrix}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
