-align: -0.671ex; width:7.911ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1.5=
{\text{ IQR}}}"></span> for both whiskers.
</p><p><b>Other kinds of box plots</b>, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Violin_plot" title=3D"Violin plot">violin plots</a> and t=
he bean plots can show the difference between single-modal and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multimodal_distribution" title=3D"Multimodal d=
istribution">multimodal</a> distributions, which cannot be observed from th=
e original classical box-plot.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_6-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot#cite_note-:0-6"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Example_without_outliers">E=
xample without outliers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DBox_plot&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Example without outliers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:No_Outlier.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/No_O=
utlier.png/250px-No_Outlier.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"190" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"720" data-file-height=3D=
"547"></a><figcaption>A boxplot with no outliers</figcaption></figure>
<p>A series of hourly temperatures were measured throughout the day in degr=
ees Fahrenheit. The recorded values are listed in order as follows (=C2=B0F=
): 57, 57, 57, 58, 63, 66, 66, 67, 67, 68, 69, 70, 70, 70, 70, 72, 73, 75, =
75, 76, 76, 78, 79, 81.
</p><p>A box plot of the data set can be generated by first calculating fiv=
e relevant values of this data set: minimum, maximum, median (<b><i>Q</i><s=
ub>2</sub></b>), first quartile (<b><i>Q</i><sub>1</sub></b>), and third qu=
artile (<b><i>Q</i><sub>3</sub></b>).
</p><p>The minimum is the smallest number of the data set. In this case, th=
e minimum recorded day temperature is 57=C2=B0F.
</p><p>The maximum is the largest number of the data set. In this case, the=
 maximum recorded day temperature is 81=C2=B0F.
</p><p>The median is the "middle" number of the ordered data set. This mean=
s that exactly 50% of the elements are below the median and 50% of the elem=
ents are greater than the median. The median of this ordered data set is 70=
=C2=B0F.
</p><p>The first quartile value (<b><i>Q</i><sub>1</sub></b> <b>or 25th per=
centile)</b> is the number that marks one quarter of the ordered data set. =
In other words, there are exactly 25% of the elements that are less than th=
e first quartile and exactly 75% of the elements that are greater than it. =
The first quartile value can be easily determined by finding the "middle" n=
umber between the minimum and the median. For the hourly temperatures, the =
"middle" number found between 57=C2=B0F and 70=C2=B0F is 66=C2=B0F.
</p><p>The third quartile value (<b><i>Q</i><sub>3</sub></b> <b>or 75th per=
centile)</b> is the number that marks three quarters of the ordered data se=
t. In other words, there are exactly 75% of the elements that are less than=
 the third quartile and 25% of the elements that are greater than it. The t=
hird quartile value can be easily obtained by finding the "middle" number b=
etween the median and the maximum. For the hourly temperatures, the "middle=
" number between 70=C2=B0F and 81=C2=B0F is 75=C2=B0F.
</p><p>The interquartile range, or IQR, can be calculated by subtracting th=
e first quartile value (<b><i>Q</i><sub>1</sub></b>) from the third quartil=
e value (<b><i>Q</i><sub>3</sub></b>):
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\text{IQR}}=3DQ_{3}-Q_{1}=3D75^{\circ }F-66^{\circ }F=3D9^{\circ }F.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>IQR</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
